<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="537" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="537">
Carapace pyriform with spines. Pseudorostral spines relatively long, straight, stout, cylindrical, slight diverging at approximately 20° angle or less. Supraorbital eave with blunt preorbital angle; weak postorbital lobe small, round anterior margin. Carapace with strong spines; 3 spines medially: metagastric, cardiac, intestinal; strong lateral branchial spines pointed outwards and downwards (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Illustration of Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), Mediterranean. A. overall dorsal view; B. male pleon; C. female pleon. (After Roux 1828: pl. 3)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447933" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">16A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (22.9 x 16.1 mm) (SMF 4420), North Atlantic Ocean. A. overall dorsal view; B. overall ventral view; C. lateral view of carapace." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447934" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">17A</figureCitation>
). Antennal flagellum shorter than pseudorostral spines (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (22.9 x 16.1 mm) (SMF 4420), North Atlantic Ocean. A. overall dorsal view; B. overall ventral view; C. lateral view of carapace." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447934" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">17B</figureCitation>
). Basal antennal article longer than broad, distal angle blunt, relatively straight outer margin. Distal angle of buccal frame elongated, forming strong blunt angle. Pterygostomial region with granules on outer margin (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (22.9 x 16.1 mm) (SMF 4420), North Atlantic Ocean. A. overall dorsal view; B. overall ventral view; C. lateral view of carapace." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447934" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">17B</figureCitation>
). Chelipeds slender, articles with rounded margins; propodus slender, longer than fingers; carpus with spines on outer margin; merus with spine on distal angle, rounded margins. Ambulatory legs slender, articles with rounded margins; merus with blunt distal angle; P2 longest (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Illustration of Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), Mediterranean. A. overall dorsal view; B. male pleon; C. female pleon. (After Roux 1828: pl. 3)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447933" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">16A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (22.9 x 16.1 mm) (SMF 4420), North Atlantic Ocean. A. overall dorsal view; B. overall ventral view; C. lateral view of carapace." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447934" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">17A</figureCitation>
). Male thoracic sternum concave anteriorly, constricted between sternites 1, 2 and 3, 4; sternites 3, 4 with lateral margin slightly constricted. Male pleon triangular, telson triangular, margin round; with raised granules on somites 2-5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (22.9 x 16.1 mm) (SMF 4420), North Atlantic Ocean. A. overall dorsal view; B. overall ventral view; C. lateral view of carapace." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447934" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">17B</figureCitation>
). G1 straight with flattened sharp tip (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (26.2 x 17.5 mm) (SMF 4410), North Atlantic Ocean, left G 1 and G 2. A. ventral view; B. ventral view of distal portion; C. dorsal view; D. dorsal view of distal portion; E. ventral view of G 2; F. dorsal view of G 2. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447935" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">18A-D</figureCitation>
); G2 with distal tip round (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Anamathia rissoana (Roux, 1828), male (26.2 x 17.5 mm) (SMF 4410), North Atlantic Ocean, left G 1 and G 2. A. ventral view; B. ventral view of distal portion; C. dorsal view; D. dorsal view of distal portion; E. ventral view of G 2; F. dorsal view of G 2. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.96.48041.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/447935" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">18E, F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="537" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="537">
The genus was first described as 
<taxonomicName class="Gymnolaemata" family="Vesiculariidae" genus="Amathia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amathia" order="Ctenostomatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Amathia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Roux, P" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of Museum Victoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" refId="B109" refString="Roux, P, 1828-1830. Crustaces de la Mediterranee et de son littoral. Levrault, Paris, [iv] + [176] pp., pls. 1-45. [Note: Pages not numbered] [Published in 9 parts. Parts 1, 2 (pls. 1-10): 1828; Part 3 (pls. 11-15): 1829; Parts 4-9 (pls. 16-45): 1830; see Manning and Holthuis (1981: 374) and Monod (1956: 646).]" title="Crustaces de la Mediterranee et de son littoral. Levrault, Paris, [iv] + [176] pp., pls. 1 - 45. [Note: Pages not numbered] [Published in 9 parts. Parts 1, 2 (pls. 1 - 10): 1828; Part 3 (pls. 11 - 15): 1829; Parts 4 - 9 (pls. 16 - 45): 1830; see Manning and Holthuis (1981: 374) and Monod (1956: 646).]" year="1828 - 1830">Roux (1828)</bibRefCitation>
. The name was changed to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1885" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Anamathia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anamathia" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Anamathia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00963801.455.493" author="Smith, SI" journalOrPublisher="Crustaceana" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" refId="B116" refString="Smith, SI, 1885. On some new or little known decapod Crustacea, from recent fish commission dredgings off the east coast of the United Sates. Proceedings of the United States National Museum VII (31): 493-496. [26 Jan.1885]. https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00963801.455.493" title="On some new or little known decapod Crustacea, from recent fish commission dredgings off the east coast of the United Sates. Proceedings of the United States National Museum VII (31): 493 - 496. [26 Jan. 1885]." url="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00963801.455.493" year="1885">Smith (1885)</bibRefCitation>
, as the earlier name was preoccupied for a bryozoan (
<bibRefCitation author="Lamouroux, JVF" journalOrPublisher="Nouveau Bulletin des Sciences, par la Societe Philomatique, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" pagination="181 - 188" refId="B56" refString="Lamouroux, JVF, 1812. Extrait d'un memoire sur la classification des polypiers coralligenes non entierement pierreux. Nouveau Bulletin des Sciences, par la Societe Philomatique, Paris 63: 181 - 188" title="Extrait d'un memoire sur la classification des polypiers coralligenes non entierement pierreux." volume="63" year="1812">Lamouroux 1812</bibRefCitation>
). This genus was synonymised by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.03629236.129.i" author="Rathbun, MJ" journalOrPublisher="United States National Museum Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" pagination="1 - 613" refId="B101" refString="Rathbun, MJ, 1925. The spider crabs of America. United States National Museum Bulletin 129: 1 - 613, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5479/si.03629236.129.i" title="The spider crabs of America." url="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.03629236.129.i" volume="129" year="1925">Rathbun (1925)</bibRefCitation>
under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1875" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rochinia" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, with no detailed explanation. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ng, PKL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Crustacean Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" refId="B85" refString="Ng, PKL, Guinot, D, Davie, PJF, 2008. Systema Brachyurorum: part I. An annotated checklist of extant brachyuran crabs of the world. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 17 (supplement): 1-286." title="Systema Brachyurorum: part I. An annotated checklist of extant brachyuran crabs of the world. Raffles Bulletin of Zoology 17 (supplement): 1 - 286." year="2008">Ng et al. (2008)</bibRefCitation>
listed the genus as valid as well but again with no explanation. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" author="Tavares, MS" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" pagination="201 - 227" refId="B126" refString="Tavares, MS, Santana, W, 2018. Refining the genus Rochinia A. Milne-Edwards, 1875: reinstatement of Scyramathia A. Milne-Edwards, 1880 and Anamathia Smith, 1885, and a new genus for Amathia crassa A. Milne-Edwards, 1879, with notes on its ontogeny (Crustacea: Brachyura: Epialtidae). Zootaxa 4418 (3): 201 - 227, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" title="Refining the genus Rochinia A. Milne-Edwards, 1875: reinstatement of Scyramathia A. Milne-Edwards, 1880 and Anamathia Smith, 1885, and a new genus for Amathia crassa A. Milne-Edwards, 1879, with notes on its ontogeny (Crustacea: Brachyura: Epialtidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" volume="4418" year="2018">Tavares and Santana (2018)</bibRefCitation>
discussed the matter and considered this genus as valid, listing the morphological differences from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1875" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rochinia" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1880" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Scyramathia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scyramathia" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Scyramathia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Anamathia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anamathia hystrix" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hystrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Anamathia hystrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Stimpson, 1871) was also transferred to this genus by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" author="Tavares, MS" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" pagination="201 - 227" refId="B126" refString="Tavares, MS, Santana, W, 2018. Refining the genus Rochinia A. Milne-Edwards, 1875: reinstatement of Scyramathia A. Milne-Edwards, 1880 and Anamathia Smith, 1885, and a new genus for Amathia crassa A. Milne-Edwards, 1879, with notes on its ontogeny (Crustacea: Brachyura: Epialtidae). Zootaxa 4418 (3): 201 - 227, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" title="Refining the genus Rochinia A. Milne-Edwards, 1875: reinstatement of Scyramathia A. Milne-Edwards, 1880 and Anamathia Smith, 1885, and a new genus for Amathia crassa A. Milne-Edwards, 1879, with notes on its ontogeny (Crustacea: Brachyura: Epialtidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4418.3.1" volume="4418" year="2018">Tavares and Santana (2018)</bibRefCitation>
without explanation. Although the external features of this species resemble 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. rissoana" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" rank="species" species="rissoana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">A. rissoana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. hystrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" rank="species" species="hystrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">R. hystrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a strong preorbital spine and a pronounced mesogastric spine in the middle of the carapace; and on the basis of this as well as unpublished genetic data, we are of the opinion that it should not be placed in this genus. As such, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. hystrix" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" rank="species" species="hystrix">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">R. hystrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
together with the rest of the Atlantic and East Pacific 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1875" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rochinia" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="537">Rochinia</emphasis>
